## REVISION (2026-06-03): Refined Workers streaming approach

### spawn_local + TransformStream pattern

After reviewing the Cloudflare Workers Rust SDK and web_sys bindings, the concrete implementation pattern is:

```rust
use wasm_bindgen_futures::spawn_local;
use web_sys::TransformStream;

pub async fn handle_streaming(kv: KvStore, env: Env, ...) -> Result<Response> {
    // 1. Create the stream
    let transform = TransformStream::new().map_err(|e| ...)?;
    let readable = transform.readable();
    let writer = transform.writable().get_writer().map_err(|e| ...)?;

    // 2. Move everything the producer needs into spawn_local
    spawn_local(async move {
        // Write initial comment to confirm connection
        write_sse(&writer, ": connected\n\n").await;

        for round_num in start..end {
            write_sse(&writer, &format_round_start(round_num)).await;

            match execute_round(&kv, &env, &wf, name, round_num, &overrides).await {
                Ok(result) => {
                    write_sse(&writer, &format_round_complete(&result)).await;
                    // check convergence, break if needed
                }
                Err(e) => {
                    write_sse(&writer, &format_error(round_num, &e)).await;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        // Final aggregate event
        write_sse(&writer, &format_done(&aggregate)).await;
        let _ = writer.close();
    });

    // 3. Return streaming response immediately
    let resp = Response::from_stream(readable)?;
    let mut headers = Headers::new();
    headers.set("Content-Type", "text/event-stream")?;
    headers.set("Cache-Control", "no-cache")?;
    headers.set("Connection", "keep-alive")?;
    Ok(resp.with_headers(headers))
}
```

Key insight: the handler returns the Response (with the readable side) IMMEDIATELY. The spawn_local closure continues writing to the writable side. The Worker stays alive because the ReadableStream is still open — Cloudflare ties isolate lifetime to open response streams.

### Keepalive comments

SSE allows comment lines (starting with `:`) that don't trigger client events but DO keep the TCP connection alive. We should emit keepalive comments during long LLM calls:

```
: keepalive 2026-06-03T10:05:30Z
```

But since execute_round is a single await (it blocks until the round completes), we can't inject keepalive comments DURING a round. The events flow BETWEEN rounds only.

For typical round durations (30-60s), one event every 30-60s is enough to prevent most proxy timeouts. Only extremely aggressive proxies (< 30s idle timeout) would be a problem, and those would also kill single-round POST /run calls.

If keepalive during rounds becomes necessary, we'd need to restructure execute_round to yield periodic progress, which is a bigger change. For v1, inter-round events are sufficient.

### Error in spawn_local

If spawn_local panics or encounters an unrecoverable error, the writable side is dropped, which closes the readable stream. The client sees the stream end abruptly. This is the same failure mode as a Worker crash — the client should handle stream disconnection gracefully.

To be safe, wrap the entire spawn_local body in a catch_unwind or use Result-based error handling throughout.

## REVISION (2026-06-03): Clarified implementation — pre-substitution approach

After reviewing prompt.rs and the render_template function, the cleanest implementation is OPTION A: pre-substitute {{previous_round}} BEFORE calling render_template, not modify render_template itself.

### Why pre-substitution beats modifying render_template

render_template does: extract placeholders → map to document roles → fetch from KV via doc::<workflow>::<role>. The {{previous_round}} content lives in round::<workflow>::<N-1>.content, not in doc::<workflow>::previous_round. Forcing it through render_template would require either:
- Writing a temporary KV key (wasteful, needs cleanup)
- Adding a synthetic documents parameter to render_template (complicates the interface for one special case)

Pre-substitution is 10 lines of code in execute_round, no changes to prompt.rs rendering logic:

```rust
// Inside execute_round, after select_template, before render_template
let effective_template = if template.contains("{{previous_round}}") {
    if round > 1 {
        let prev = kv_get::<Round>(kv, &round_key(workflow_name, round - 1)).await?;
        let prev_content = prev
            .and_then(|r| r.content)
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "(Prior round has no content.)".to_string());
        template.replace("{{previous_round}}", &prev_content)
    } else {
        template.replace("{{previous_round}}", "(This is the first review round — no prior analysis available.)")
    }
} else {
    template.to_string()
};
// Then pass effective_template to render_template instead of template
```

### Template validation in workflows.rs

The workflow creation endpoint (POST /workflows) validates that all template placeholders have corresponding entries in the documents map. {{previous_round}} would fail this validation.

Fix: in workflows.rs's placeholder validation, skip "previous_round" as a recognized synthetic placeholder. Add it to a SYNTHETIC_PLACEHOLDERS constant:

```rust
const SYNTHETIC_PLACEHOLDERS: &[&str] = &["previous_round"];
```

### DEFAULT_TEMPLATE must NOT change

The existing DEFAULT_TEMPLATE and DEFAULT_TEMPLATE_WITH_IMPL in prompt.rs MUST remain unchanged. This preserves backwards compatibility for all existing workflows. {{previous_round}} is ONLY available when a workflow provides a custom template that explicitly includes the placeholder.

We do NOT add a new default template variant. Users who want iterative refinement must write their own template. This keeps the feature opt-in and preserves the independent-review mode as the default behavior.

### Works with POST /run too

Since pre-substitution happens in execute_round (not in auto.rs), the {{previous_round}} feature automatically works with single-round POST /run calls too. POST /run/demo/5 would inject round 4's content if the workflow template includes {{previous_round}}. No auto-run required.

